claim.claim-text:
1. A method of forming a non-volatile resistive switching memory element, the method comprising:
forming a first electrode on a substrate;
forming a composite metal oxide layer over the first electrode by an atomic layer deposition (ALD) process; and
forming a second electrode over the composite metal oxide layer;
wherein the composite metal oxide layer comprises electrically active defects;
wherein the composite metal oxide layer comprises a first metal oxide and a second metal oxide; and
wherein the first metal oxide is different from the second metal oxide.

2. The method of claim 1, wherein the composite metal oxide layer comprises a first sub-layer and a second sub-layer;
wherein the first sub-layer comprises the first metal oxide; and
wherein the second sub-layer comprises the second metal oxide.

4. The method of claim 1, wherein the first metal oxide is formed using a first metal-containing precursor;
wherein the second metal oxide is formed using a second metal-containing precursor;
and wherein the first metal-containing precursor and the second metal-containing precursor are co-injected into an ALD chamber containing the substrate.

20. A method of forming a non-volatile resistive switching memory element, the method comprising:
forming a first electrode on a substrate;
forming a metal oxide layer over the first electrode; and

forming a second electrode over the metal oxide layer;
wherein the first electrode comprises titanium nitride sputtered by bombarding a metal target at 150-500 W with a pressure of 2-10 mTorr;
wherein the metal oxide layer comprises electrically active defects; and
wherein the metal oxide layer is formed using an atomic layer deposition (ALD) process at a substrate temperature of less than 100° C.
